NLquery: For each Internet Service(sid), find the most frequently used version among all Base Models that utilize it. If multiple versions have the same highest frequency, you may return any one of them.
prompt: Translate this natural language query into SQL format: For each Internet Service (sid), find the most frequently used version among all Base Models that utilize it. If multiple versions have the same highest frequency, you may return any one of them.
LLM_returned_SQL_query: SELECT sid, version FROM ( SELECT sid, version, ROW_NUMBER() OVER ( PARTITION BY sid ORDER BY COUNT(*) DESC ) AS rn FROM BaseModels GROUP BY sid, version ) AS t WHERE rn = 1;

NLquery: For each Internet Service(sid), find the most frequently used version among all Base Models that utilize it. If multiple versions have the same highest frequency, you may return any one of them.
prompt: Achieve this NL2SQL task from the given natural language query and table schema: NL query: For each Internet Service (sid), find the most frequently used version among all Base Models that utilize it. If multiple versions have the same highest frequency, you may return any one of them. Table schema: BaseModel(bmid, creator_uid, description), ModelServices(bmid, sid, version), InternetService(sid, provider, endpoints)
LLM_returned_SQL_query: SELECT ms.sid, ms.version FROM ModelServices ms JOIN (SELECT sid, version, ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY sid ORDER BY COUNT(*) DESC) AS rn FROM ModelServices GROUP BY sid, version) ranked ON ms.sid = ranked.sid AND ms.version = ranked.version WHERE ranked.rn = 1;

NLquery: For each Internet Service(sid), find the most frequently used version among all Base Models that utilize it. If multiple versions have the same highest frequency, you may return any one of them.
prompt: Pretend that you’re a SQL expert. Given the following schema and example question, write the correct SQL query based on the following natural language prompt: For each Internet Service (sid), find the most frequently used version among all Base Models that utilize it. If multiple versions have the same highest frequency, you may return any one of them. Table schema: BaseModel(bmid, creator_uid, description) ModelServices(bmid, sid, version) InternetService(sid, provider, endpoints). Here’s an example of translating natural language queries into SQL: NL query: 'List all users and their emails.' SQL query: 'SELECT uid, email FROM User;'
LLM_returned_SQL_query: SELECT sid, version FROM (SELECT sid, version, RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY sid ORDER BY COUNT(*) DESC) AS rnk FROM ModelServices GROUP BY sid, version) t WHERE rnk = 1;

NLquery: Find all the Internet Service(sid) that are utilized by every Base Model built by the agent creator user_iuwrh.
prompt: Translate this natural language query into SQL format: Find all the Internet Service(sid) that are utilized by every Base Model built by the agent creator user_iuwrh.
LLM_returned_SQL_query: SELECT bms.service_id FROM BaseModelService AS bms JOIN BaseModel AS bm ON bm.id = bms.base_model_id WHERE bm.creator = 'user_iuwrh' GROUP BY bms.service_id HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT bms.base_model_id) = (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM BaseModel WHERE creator = 'user_iuwrh');

NLquery: Find all the Internet Service(sid) that are utilized by every Base Model built by the agent creator user_iuwrh.
prompt: Achieve this NL2SQL task from the given natural language query and table schema: NL Query: Find all the Internet Service (sid) that are utilized by every Base Model built by the agent creator user_iuwrh. Table schema: AgentCreator(uid, bio, payout), BaseModel(bmid, creator_uid, description), ModelServices(bmid, sid, version)
LLM_returned_SQL_query: SELECT ms.sid FROM ModelServices ms WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM BaseModel bm WHERE bm.creator_uid = 'user_iuwrh' AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM ModelServices ms2 WHERE ms2.bmid = bm.bmid AND ms2.sid = ms.sid)) GROUP BY ms.sid;

NLquery: Find all the Internet Service(sid) that are utilized by every Base Model built by the agent creator user_iuwrh.
prompt: Pretend you’re a SQL expert who is very proficient in translating natural language questions into SQL queries. Convert the following natural language question into a correct MySQL SQL query: Find all the Internet Service (sid) that are utilized by every Base Model built by the agent creator user_iuwrh. Table schema: User(uid, email, username), BaseModel(bmid,creator_uid, description), ModelServices(bmid, sid, version). creator_uid in BaseModel references User.uid and user_iuwrh refers to the username, not the uid. The query must return only services used by all base models built by that user. For example, if a user has base models 1 and 2, and service 3 appears in both models, then service 3 should be included in the result
LLM_returned_SQL_query: SELECT ms.sid FROM ModelServices ms JOIN BaseModel bm ON ms.bmid = bm.bmid JOIN User u ON bm.creator_uid = u.uid WHERE u.username = 'user_iuwrh' GROUP BY ms.sid HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT ms.bmid) = (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM BaseModel bm2 JOIN User u2 ON bm2.creator_uid = u2.uid WHERE u2.username = 'user_iuwrh');

NLquery: Find all customized models(mid) that do not appear in model configurations.
prompt: Translate this natural language query into SQL format: Find all customized models(mid) that do not appear in model configurations.
LLM_returned_SQL_query: SELECT mid FROM customized_models WHERE mid NOT IN (SELECT mid FROM model_configurations);

NLquery: Find all customized models(mid) that do not appear in model configurations.
prompt: Achieve this NL2SQL task from the given natural language query and table schema: NL query: Find all customized models(mid) that do not appear in model configurations. Table schema: CustomizedModel(bmid, mid), ModelConfiguration(bmid, mid, cid, duration).
LLM_returned_SQL_query: SELECT cm.mid FROM CustomizedModel cm WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM ModelConfiguration mc WHERE mc.mid = cm.mid);

NLquery: Find all customized models(mid) that do not appear in model configurations.
prompt: Pretend you’re a SQL expert who specializes in translating natural language questions into SQL queries. Convert the following natural language question into a correct MySQL SQL query: Find all customized models(mid) that do not appear in model configurations. Include only customized models that do not appear in any model configurations. Table schema: CustomizedModel(bmid, mid), ModelConfiguration(bmid, mid, cid, duration). Just as an example, if CustomizedModel contains mid = {1, 2, 3} and ModelConfiguration contains mid = {2, 3}, the query should return mid = 1.
LLM_returned_SQL_query: SELECT cm.mid FROM CustomizedModel cm LEFT JOIN ModelConfigurations mc ON cm.mid = mc.mid WHERE mc.mid IS NULL;
